00:06:33,201 --> 00:07:00,745
a pure act of love or a pure act of generosity or an act of compassion or joy you know like giving somebody a present for their birthday but doing it just for the joyfulness of it to increase the other person's joy all those desires are to our benefit they make the heart grow see but as soon as something creeps in there which is to do with you know like I give a present so somebody will like me

36
00:07:01,079 --> 00:07:09,271
then I'm into a relationship which eventually can cause me suffering of some sort.

37
00:07:09,290 --> 00:07:11,415
So now he wants to reinforce that, you see.

38
00:07:11,735 --> 00:07:14,639
So now he gets to be more personal.

39
00:07:18,886 --> 00:07:22,350
So this man repeats to the Buddha, right, well, this is the root of desire.

40
00:07:22,430 --> 00:07:26,257
And then he tells him, he says, look, Venerable Sir, I have a son called Chirovati.

41
00:07:26,276 --> 00:07:26,918
So now he's

42
00:07:27,067 --> 00:07:36,038
This man, in his insight, is now linking it to the relationship he has to his son, who stays at an outside residence.

43
00:07:36,057 --> 00:07:41,644
And I rise early and send a man, saying, go, man, and find out how Chiravasi is.

44
00:07:41,985 --> 00:07:48,374
And until that man returns, Venerable Sir, I'm upset, thinking, I hope Chiravasi has not met with any affliction.

45
00:07:49,115 --> 00:07:50,255
So there's a parent's worry.

46
00:07:51,367 --> 00:08:02,543
And what do you think, headman, replies the Buddha, if Chiravasi were to be executed in prison, fined or censured, would sorrow, lamentation, pain, dejection and despair arise in you?

47
00:08:03,165 --> 00:08:09,855
Venerable sir, if Chiravasi were to be executed in prison, fined or censured, even my life would seem futile.

48
00:08:09,915 --> 00:08:15,163
So how could sorrow, lamentation, pain, dejection and despair not arise in me?

49
00:08:16,391 --> 00:08:18,375
In this way, too, has managed to be understood.

50
00:08:18,495 --> 00:08:27,189
Whatever suffering arises, all that arises rooted in desire, with desire as its source, for desire is the root of suffering.

51
00:08:27,209 --> 00:08:36,764
Now, you know, you've got to make these statements, you know, you have to sort of repeat them and let them sort of sink in.

52
00:08:36,804 --> 00:08:38,488
They sort of have to be digested.

53
00:08:38,849 --> 00:08:40,932
I mean, he's saying, what the Buddha is saying is,

54
00:08:41,501 --> 00:08:48,913
Whatever suffering arises, all that arises rooted in desire.

55
00:08:48,933 --> 00:08:51,197
You have to keep repeating that.

56
00:08:51,639 --> 00:08:55,846
Remember, suffering is not the same as pain, physical pain.

57
00:08:56,046 --> 00:08:58,890
That's a given, you know.

58
00:08:59,311 --> 00:09:04,099
But whatever suffering arises, all that arises rooted in desire.

59
00:09:04,320 --> 00:09:08,285
With desire as its source, for desire is the root of suffering.

60
00:09:09,328 --> 00:09:21,267
These phrases have a real power when you just gently repeat them to yourself in the quietness, in some sort of way in which you can feel the digestion.

61
00:09:21,287 --> 00:09:30,980
You don't have to think about it, because it's going in, it's like osmosis, you're absorbing it, and it's actually beginning to change your attitude by doing that.

62
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:34,025
That's the way spiritual reading works.

63
00:09:34,046 --> 00:09:35,488
You don't have to think about it.

64
00:09:39,653 --> 00:09:41,375
And then he wants to really drive it home.

65
00:09:41,816 --> 00:09:42,857
This is the final nail.

66
00:09:44,760 --> 00:09:45,782
What do you think, headman?

67
