68
00:09:53,352 --> 00:09:54,134
No, venerable sir.

69
00:09:54,835 --> 00:09:56,437
Then what was it, headman?

70
00:09:56,899 --> 00:10:03,388
Then was it, headman, only when you saw her or heard about her that this desire, attachment and affection rose in you?

71
00:10:03,948 --> 00:10:04,730
Yes, venerable sir.

72
00:10:04,870 --> 00:10:06,032
Now what do you think, headman?

73
00:10:06,451 --> 00:10:16,081
If your wife were to be executed, imprisoned, fined or censured, would sorrow, lamentation, pain and despair arise in you?

74
00:10:16,601 --> 00:10:23,208
Venerable sir, if my wife were to be executed, imprisoned, fined and censured, even my life would seem futile.

75
00:10:23,610 --> 00:10:28,595
So how could sorrow, lamentation, pain, dejection and despair not arise in me?

76
00:10:28,615 --> 00:10:30,277
He drives home the point.

77
00:10:30,758 --> 00:10:32,879
Well, in this way too, Hedman, it's to be understood.

78
00:10:33,248 --> 00:11:00,116
whatever suffering arises all that is rooted in desire with desire as its source for desire is the root of suffering so there's something about the the oral tradition where you know you repeat it and and and repeat it repeat it and these phrases if you when you read the scriptures

79
00:11:00,417 --> 00:11:17,798
When you come across a phrase which sort of just catches you, you know, it doesn't have to be the scriptures, it could be any spiritual work, you know, and a phrase catches you, or a sentence catches you, or even a small paragraph, you see, and you think, that's interesting, you see, don't think of it, just keep repeating it, keep repeating it.

80
00:11:18,318 --> 00:11:24,625
And you find that you keep going back to it, it's like a piece of music, and then eventually you get fed up with it.

81
00:11:25,206 --> 00:11:27,048
And at that point, you know it's been digested.

82
00:11:27,754 --> 00:11:30,157
And then it sort of comes out in funny ways.

83
00:11:30,517 --> 00:11:32,339
It actually changes the way you think.

84
00:11:32,698 --> 00:11:36,602
It comes out, as it were, through the back entrance.

85
00:11:36,623 --> 00:11:38,804
It comes out.

86
00:11:38,825 --> 00:11:40,625
And that's a beautiful way.

87
00:11:40,645 --> 00:11:50,014
This is the part, this is the way that the Benedictines, you know, that's their, they have these Lectio Meditatio, isn't it?

88
00:11:50,075 --> 00:11:50,936
Yeah.

89
00:11:50,956 --> 00:11:51,916
Contemplatio.

90
00:11:53,418 --> 00:11:53,998
I think that's right.

91
00:11:54,359 --> 00:11:56,039
So they read, see?

92
00:11:56,307 --> 00:11:58,168
And they do this repetition business.

93
00:11:58,629 --> 00:11:59,711
